  "text": "R e m a r k 1.1. Theorems E (Theorem 1.2 in [CITATION_1] ) and F (Theorem 1.3 in [CITATION_2] ) are new and seem fine. However, in the statements of both the Theorems E and F there are some contradiction. It is assumed that f and g have zeros of multiplicities at least k in Theorem E and k + 1 in Theorem F. But further authors concluded that \"f (z) = c 1 e n+1 c 2 = −1\"",
